ANTHRAX - ARGENTINA: (BUENOS AIRES) BOVINE
*******************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 17 Jan 2013
From: Ramon Noseda <rnoseda@laboratorioazul.com.ar> [edited]


Rural anthrax - Argentina, Province of Buenos Aires, Pila partido
-----------------------------------------------------------------
In the 2nd week of January 2013, a 4-year-old bull died suddenly. A metacarpal bone was submitted for analysis and _Bacillus anthracis_ was cultured from the medulla. The carcass had demonstrated blood extravasation from the natural openings. The bull was otherwise in excellent condition and had been grazing a good quality pasture on his own. The carcass was incinerated.

During the previous December [2012] there had been heavy rains with more than 20 cm [8 in] of rain, which had flooded the lower parts of the pasture.

The cattle on the estancia [ranch] is composed of over 500 head, held in adjoining pastures, and no other cases have been seen among them. It is unclear whether the animals had been vaccinated in 2012, and the ranch is in a known enzootic zone for this disease.

During the period of 1977-2011 some 11 percent of sudden deaths in Buenos Aires Province were ascribed to anthrax.

--
Dr Ramon Noseda,
CFO-Director/Microbiologist
